---
// src/pages/research/index.astro
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  door="research"
  title="Ooh, a White Paper!"
  description="The legal architecture is sound. The labor market analysis is documented. The insider objection is addressed at length. The academic paper is forthcoming."
>

  <!-- ── Door Hero — Ironic Sober Register ─────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="door-hero door-hero--research" aria-label="Research door">
      <p class="door-hero-eyebrow">Research</p>
      <h1 class="door-hero-headline">
        Ooh, a <em>white paper!</em>
      </h1>
      <div class="door-hero-rule"></div>
      <p class="door-hero-sub">
        The open questions are addressed. The insider objection gets its own section. The
        legal memorandum is available on request. The academic paper is forthcoming and will
        be here when it arrives.
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── The Legal Foundation ──────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <div class="licensed-break licensed-break--ink">
      <p>
        The skinny union rests on a legal foundation that is sound under existing law and
        does not depend on any court adopting a new rule.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── The Insider's Objection ────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="The insider objection">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Contention I</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">The Insider's Objection</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>The most interesting objection to the skinny union does not come from employers.</h2>

        <p>
          It comes from sophisticated management counsel who engage the model on its own terms —
          who understand the legal architecture, accept that it is sound, and then offer a
          prediction about what happens afterward.
        </p>

        <p>
          Their prediction runs as follows. Worker organizations are inevitably captured by their
          most motivated constituency. The members who organize most intensely, sustain engagement
          over time, participate most actively in governance, and ultimately drive bargaining
          priorities are those facing the most acute personal risk. A worker who fears discipline
          or termination has a strong, immediate, personal stake in the union's agenda; a worker
          who would prefer higher wages but is performing well and has outside options has a weaker,
          more diffuse one.
        </p>

        <p>
          Over time, the dynamics of internal governance favor the motivated over the mobile.
          Even if the founding cohort is a group of strong performers whose primary concern is
          compensation, the workers who stay most engaged — who show up to meetings, run for
          office, care most about the next contract — will increasingly be those facing
          employment-security concerns. The union's bargaining mandate drifts, through member
          politics rather than formal amendment, toward the protections those members need.
        </p>

        <p>
          The objection is sophisticated and deserves a direct answer. It has two.
        </p>

        <p>
          The first is empirical: the founding population of a skinny union is precisely the
          workers for whom traditional unions offer the least — strong performers in liquid
          labor markets who would not trade compensation leverage for employment protection.
          The compensation problem this population faces cuts sharpest against the strong
          performer, not the marginal one. That profile does not predict the internal governance
          failure the objection describes.
        </p>

        <p>
          The second is structural: the skinny union's CBA scope is a materially higher bar than
          political drift. A formal agreement to bargain only over wages and benefits is not
          undone by a motivated minority pushing for grievance procedures. Reopening scope
          requires the employer's agreement. The model's legal architecture is not a norm to
          drift from — it is a contract term to renegotiate. That changes the internal politics
          considerably.
        </p>

        <blockquote class="pull-quote">
          The academic community that engages the objection critically, rather than setting it
          aside, will advance the field either way.
        </blockquote>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── The Advocacy Publication ───────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="The advocacy publication">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Document I</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Advocacy Publication</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>The full argument, documented.</h2>
        <p>
          The advocacy publication sets out the complete case for the skinny union model —
          the labor market analysis, the legal architecture under existing NLRA doctrine, the
          organizing mechanics, and the response to the primary objections. It is the keystone
          document of the project.
        </p>
        <div class="placeholder">
          <span class="placeholder-label">Available — Advocacy Publication (Draft 6)</span>
          <p>
            Full publication forthcoming as an HTML document on this page. Available on
            request in the interim.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Legal Memorandum ───────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Legal memorandum">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Document II</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">Legal Memorandum</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>The doctrinal analysis.</h2>
        <p>
          A detailed memorandum analyzing the legal architecture of the skinny union under
          existing NLRA doctrine — the scope-limitation framework, the recognition mechanics,
          the CBA model language, and the doctrinal stability of each element. Prepared by
          independent labor counsel.
        </p>
        <div class="placeholder">
          <span class="placeholder-label">Available on Request — Legal Memorandum (Draft 8)</span>
          <p>
            The legal memorandum is available to qualified researchers, journalists, and
            practitioners. Contact information forthcoming.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Academic Paper ─────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Academic paper">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Document III</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--gold">Forthcoming</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>The academic paper.</h2>
        <div class="placeholder">
          <span class="placeholder-label">Forthcoming — Academic Paper</span>
          <p>
            A law review–grade treatment of the skinny union model: labor market theory,
            doctrinal analysis, and engagement with the academic objection. Authorized.
            In preparation.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Open Questions ─────────────────────────────────── -->
  <div class="page-body">
    <section class="spec-section" aria-label="Open questions">
      <div class="col-structural">
        <span class="section-number">Questions</span>
        <span class="section-label section-label--cobalt">The Open Questions</span>
      </div>
      <div class="col-main">
        <h2>What this project does not yet know.</h2>
        <p>
          The skinny union model is legally sound and theoretically coherent. The open questions
          are empirical: whether a founding cohort of professional workers will, in practice,
          maintain the scope discipline the model requires; what the distribution of outcomes
          looks like across the first wave of voluntary-recognition agreements; and whether the
          governance dynamics the insider objection predicts materialize over time.
        </p>
        <p>
          The project's view is that these are better answered by doing it than by theorizing
          further. The legal architecture supports five agreements in two years with willing
          employers. Those five agreements are the proof of concept.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>
